.TE
.PP
When error happen, use getLastErrMsg() to get the error message or use
getLastError() to get the error code.
See troubleshooting for more detail.
.SH HISTORY
.PP
Since v1.0.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP "1." 3
Create collection "bar" in collection space "foo" without sharding key.
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.createCL(\ "bar"\ )
localhost:11810.foo.bar
Takes\ 0.1250s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP "2." 3
Create collection "bar" in collection space "foo".
If the collection splits data into other replication groups, it will use the age
field for hash segmentation.
It has data compression enabled by default, using the default lzw algorithm.When
a write operation is applied to the collection, it only needs to be written to
the primary node to be returned.
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.createCL(\ "bar",\ {\ ShardingKey:{\ age:\ 1\ },\ ShardingType:\ "hash",\ 
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ Partition:\ 4096,\ ReplSize:\ 1\ }\ )
localhost:11810.foo.bar
Takes\ 0.32450s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP "3." 3
Create collection "bar" in collection space "foo" with the StrictDataMode turn
on.
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.createCL(\ "bar",\ {\ StrictDataMode:\ true\ }\ )
localhost:11810.foo.bar
Takes\ 0.1250s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP "4." 3
Deal with main collection with lob.
.RS 4
.IP \[bu] 2
Create a main collection "maincl" in collection space "foo" with
LobShardingKeyFormat "YYYYMMDD".
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.createCL("maincl",\ {\ LobShardingKeyFormat:"YYYYMMDD",\ ShardingKey:{\ date:1\ },\ IsMainCL:true,\ ShardingType:"range"\ }\ )
localhost:11810.foo.maincl
Takes\ 0.058532s.
>\ db.foo.createCL("subcl")
localhost:11810.foo.subcl
Takes\ 0.294612s.
>\ db.foo.maincl.attachCL(\ "foo.subcl",\ {\ LowBound:\ {\ date:\ "20190701"\ },\ UpBound:\ {\ date:\ "20190801"\ }\ }\ )
Takes\ 0.008561s.
\f[]
.fi
.IP \[bu] 2
Time between[20190701, 20190801), Lob which is putted into collection "maincl"
will be actually stored in foo.subcl
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ Timestamp()
Timestamp("2019\-07\-23\-18.04.07.539050")
>\ db.foo.maincl.putLob(\[aq]/opt/data/test.dat\[aq])
00005d36dbee370002de8080
Takes\ 0.246062s.
\f[]
.fi
.IP \[bu] 2
Time can be specified to a particular time.
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.maincl.createLobID("2019\-07\-23\-18.04.07.539050")
00005d36db97360002de8081
Takes\ 0.108365s.
>\ db.foo.maincl.putLob(\[aq]/opt/data/test.dat\[aq],\ \[aq]00005d36db97360002de8081\[aq])
00005d36db97360002de8081
Takes\ 0.002216s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.SH MATTERS NEEDING ATTENTION
.PP
After creating the primary partition collection (the primary table) or
subpartition collection, there are some special cases to be taken into account
when using the primary/subpartition collection.
.IP "1." 3
Insert is performed from the primary partition collection, and the property uses
the corresponding property of the primary partition collection.
.IP "2." 3
Insert is performed from a subpartition collection, and the property uses the
corresponding property of the subpartition collection.
.SS Example
.PP
Validates the use of AutoIncrement when writing from the primary partition
collection and subpartition collections.
.IP "1." 3
Create primary partition collection "masterCL", and AutoIncrement set to
"masterID".
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.createCL("masterCL",{\ IsMainCL:\ true,\ ShardingKey:\ {\ a:\ 1\ },\ ShardingType:\ "range",\ AutoIncrement:\ {\ Field:\ "masterID"\ }\ })
localhost:11810.foo.masterCL
Takes\ 0.002450s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP "2." 3
Create subpartition collection "slaveCL", and AutoIncrement set to "slaveID".
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.createCL("slaveCL",{\ ShardingKey:\ {\ b:\ 1\ },\ ShardingType:\ "hash",\ Partition:\ 1024,\ AutoIncrement:\ {\ Field:\ "slaveID"\ }})
localhost:11810.foo.slaveCL
Takes\ 0.263536s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP "3." 3
Subpartition collection "slaveCL" attach to primary partition collection
"masterCL".
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.masterCL.attachCL(\ "foo.slaveCL",\ {\ LowBound:\ {\ a:\ 0\ },\ UpBound:\ {\ a:\ 100\ }\ }\ )
localhost:11810.foo.slaveCL
Takes\ 0.002743s.
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP "4." 3
When inserting data from the primary partition: masterCL, AutoIncrement will use
the corresponding property of the primary partition collection, so the data
{"a":1} will have "masterID".
When inserting data from the subpartition collection: slaveCL, AutoIncrement
will use the corresponding property of the subpartition collection, so the data
{"a":2} will have "slaveID".
.nf
\f[C]
>\ db.foo.masterCL.insert({"a":1})\ //inserting\ data\ from\ masterCL
Takes\ 0.001877s.\ 
>\ db.foo.slaveCL.insert({"a":2})\ //inserting\ data\ from\ slaveCL
Takes\ 0.001238s.
>\ db.foo.masterCL.find()\ //get\ results
{
\ \ "_id":\ {
\ \ \ \ "$oid":\ "5d42b40d2d7dfa6391e3cbd9"
\ \ },
\ \ "a":\ 1,
\ \ "masterID":\ 1
}
{
\ \ "_id":\ {
\ \ \ \ "$oid":\ "5d42b4342d7dfa6391e3cbda"
\ \ },
\ \ "a":\ 2,
\ \ "slaveID":\ 1
}
Return\ 2\ row(s).
Takes\ 0.001234s.
>\ 
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.PP
For other properties of the collection, such as ShardingKey, Compressed,
AutoIndexId and so on, the subpartition collection uses its own properties
instead of the properties of the primary partition collection .
